✅ [DEBUG] MODEL-ANSWER RESPONSE (Group 13):
<span class="model_question">
A right-angled triangle is formed by the diameters of three semicircular regions, A, B and C as shown in the diagram. Show that area of region A = area of region B + area of region C.
</span>
<div class="model_answer">
Let the diameters of the semicircles A, B, and C be $d_A$, $d_B$, and $d_C$ respectively.
By Pythagoras' theorem, $d_A^2 = d_B^2 + d_C^2$ <span class="marking-code">[M1]</span>
<br>
Area of semicircle A $= \frac{1}{2} \pi (\frac{d_A}{2})^2$
<br>
Area of semicircle B $= \frac{1}{2} \pi (\frac{d_B}{2})^2$
<br>
Area of semicircle C $= \frac{1}{2} \pi (\frac{d_C}{2})^2$ <span class="marking-code">[M1]</span>
<br>
Area of B + Area of C $= \frac{1}{2} \pi (\frac{d_B}{2})^2 + \frac{1}{2} \pi (\frac{d_C}{2})^2 = \frac{1}{2} \pi (\frac{d_B^2}{4} + \frac{d_C^2}{4}) = \frac{1}{8} \pi (d_B^2 + d_C^2)$
<br>
Since $d_A^2 = d_B^2 + d_C^2$, Area of B + Area of C $= \frac{1}{8} \pi d_A^2 = \frac{1}{2} \pi (\frac{d_A^2}{4}) = \frac{1}{2} \pi (\frac{d_A}{2})^2 =$ Area of A.
<br>
Therefore, Area of region A = Area of region B + Area of region C. <span class="marking-code">[C1]</span>
</div>

